1
00:05:18,604 --> 00:05:19,798
Get Charlie.

2
00:05:30,444 --> 00:05:32,036
Dr. Holloway!

3
00:05:34,804 --> 00:05:36,078
Charlie!

4
00:05:44,604 --> 00:05:45,320
What?

5
00:05:46,044 --> 00:05:47,796
Come quick!

6
00:06:16,404 --> 00:06:18,520
- Did you date it?
- Thirty-five thousand...

7
00:06:18,684 --> 00:06:20,640
...years. Maybe older.

8
00:06:43,404 --> 00:06:45,679
You gotta be kidding me.

9
00:06:48,444 --> 00:06:50,116
It's the same configuration.

10
00:06:51,844 --> 00:06:54,995
I mean, it's gotta predate
the others by millennia.

11
00:07:08,204 --> 00:07:10,399
I think they want us
to come and find them.

12
00:07:13,004 --> 00:07:14,039
Yeah.

13
00:08:17,284 --> 00:08:19,718
What happened to that man?

14
00:08:19,884 --> 00:08:20,919
He died.

15
00:08:22,324 --> 00:08:23,677
Why aren't you helping them?

16
00:08:24,924 --> 00:08:26,562
They don't want my help.

17
00:08:26,724 --> 00:08:28,203
Their God is different than ours.

18
00:08:30,444 --> 00:08:31,797
Why did he die?

19
00:08:32,684 --> 00:08:34,515
Because sooner or later, everyone does.

20
00:08:34,684 --> 00:08:35,878
Like Mummy?

21
00:08:37,804 --> 00:08:38,998
Like Mummy.

22
00:08:40,684 --> 00:08:42,242
Where do they go?

23
00:08:43,724 --> 00:08:45,715
Everyone has their own word.

24
00:08:45,964 --> 00:08:47,079
Heaven.

25
00:08:47,724 --> 00:08:48,520
Paradise.

26
00:08:50,284 --> 00:08:52,479
Whatever it's called,
it's someplace beautiful.

27
00:08:52,644 --> 00:08:54,236
How do you know it's beautiful?

28
00:08:56,204 --> 00:08:57,637
That's what I choose to believe.

29
00:08:57,964 --> 00:08:59,522
What do you believe, Ellie?

30
00:09:32,484 --> 00:09:34,202
Good morning, David.

31
00:09:35,244 --> 00:09:36,643
Transmitting message.

32
00:09:39,724 --> 00:09:41,476
No response.

33
00:09:50,804 --> 00:09:52,203
Whilst this articulation...

34
00:09:52,364 --> 00:09:55,003
...is attested in
the Indo-European descendants...

35
00:09:55,164 --> 00:09:56,961
...as a purely paralinguistic form...

36
00:09:57,124 --> 00:10:00,082
...it is phonemic in the ancestral form
dating back...

37
00:10:00,244 --> 00:10:02,121
...five millennia or more.

38
00:10:02,764 --> 00:10:04,197
Let's attempt Schleicher's fable.

39
00:10:04,684 --> 00:10:05,434
Repeat after me.

40
00:10:18,284 --> 00:10:19,353
Perfect.

41
00:10:19,924 --> 00:10:22,119
- Mr. Lawrence?
- Yes?

42
00:10:22,604 --> 00:10:24,435
- Flimsy, sir.
- Thank you.

43
00:10:31,204 --> 00:10:33,718
You do that once too often.
It's only flesh and blood!

44
00:10:34,444 --> 00:10:36,833
Michael George Hartley,
you're a philosopher.

45
00:10:37,364 --> 00:10:38,592
And you're barmy.

46
00:10:43,844 --> 00:10:46,119
- It damn well hurts!
- Certainly, it hurts.

47
00:10:47,204 --> 00:10:48,637
Well, what's the trick, then?

48
00:10:49,484 --> 00:10:52,442
The trick, William Potter,
is not minding that it hurts.

49
00:10:52,884 --> 00:10:56,035
The trick, William Potter...

50
00:10:56,204 --> 00:10:59,162
...is not minding that it hurts.

51
00:11:04,484 --> 00:11:07,362
The trick, William Potter...

52
00:11:07,924 --> 00:11:11,280
...is not minding that it hurts.

53
00:11:24,364 --> 00:11:25,956
Attention:

54
00:11:26,124 --> 00:11:27,477
Destination threshold.

55
00:11:27,884 --> 00:11:28,919
Attention:

56
00:11:29,084 --> 00:11:30,995
Destination threshold.

57
00:11:31,444 --> 00:11:33,833
Attention: Destination threshold.

58
00:12:33,604 --> 00:12:34,593
Robe.

59
00:12:45,604 --> 00:12:46,832
How long?

60
00:12:47,084 --> 00:12:49,279
Two years, four months, 18 days...

61
00:12:49,444 --> 00:12:50,593
...36 hours, 15 minutes.

62
00:12:50,924 --> 00:12:52,118
Any casualties?

63
00:12:52,644 --> 00:12:53,713
Casualties, ma'am?

64
00:12:53,884 --> 00:12:54,919
Has anyone died?

65
00:12:55,444 --> 00:12:57,275
No, ma'am. Everyone is fine.

66
00:12:59,284 --> 00:13:00,763
Well, then wake them up.

67
00:13:11,564 --> 00:13:13,441
Try to relax, Dr. Shaw.

68
00:13:14,604 --> 00:13:16,117
My name is David.

69
00:13:17,444 --> 00:13:19,719
Your mind and body
are in a state of shock...

70
00:13:19,884 --> 00:13:21,875
...as a result of the stasis.

71
00:13:22,124 --> 00:13:23,921
It's all right. Perfectly normal.

72
00:13:24,124 --> 00:13:24,840
Ellie.

73
00:13:26,084 --> 00:13:27,403
We're here, baby.

74
00:13:31,564 --> 00:13:32,360
There, there.

75
00:13:34,124 --> 00:13:36,240
Drink plenty of water.
Drink plenty of fluids.

76
00:13:37,724 --> 00:13:39,077
Hydration aids muscle mass.

77
00:13:44,044 --> 00:13:47,002
All crew, consume shakes
with high caloric content.

78
00:13:53,004 --> 00:13:55,074
What the hell is that?

79
00:13:57,084 --> 00:13:57,914
It's Christmas.

80
00:13:58,324 --> 00:13:59,393
We need the holidays...

81
00:13:59,564 --> 00:14:01,043
...to show time is still moving.

82
00:14:01,204 --> 00:14:02,080
Mission briefing...

83
00:14:02,244 --> 00:14:03,723
...is about to start, captain.

84
00:14:04,204 --> 00:14:05,717
Might wanna make your way down.

85
00:14:05,964 --> 00:14:08,194
Well, I haven't had any breakfast yet.

86
00:14:08,684 --> 00:14:10,037
Is this seat taken?

87
00:14:11,084 --> 00:14:13,598
Hi, I'm Millburn, Biology. Nice to meet you.

88
00:14:15,724 --> 00:14:16,440
Okay.

89
00:14:16,604 --> 00:14:19,960
Look, no offense, but...

90
00:14:20,484 --> 00:14:22,440
...I've been asleep two years.

91
00:14:23,084 --> 00:14:25,518
I ain't here to be your friend.

92
00:14:25,804 --> 00:14:27,078
I'm here to make money.

93
00:14:28,164 --> 00:14:29,438
You got that?

94
00:14:31,884 --> 00:14:33,164
Okay.

95
00:14:33,484 --> 00:14:36,078
I bet a hundred credits
it's a terraforming survey.

96
00:14:36,244 --> 00:14:38,121
No, if it's a survey, they would tell us.

97
00:14:38,284 --> 00:14:40,434
It's a corporate run,
they're not telling us shit.

98
00:14:40,604 --> 00:14:41,400
Come on.

99
00:14:41,564 --> 00:14:43,395
- A hundred.
- All right, you're on.

100
00:14:47,884 --> 00:14:49,237
You look nervous, El.

101
00:14:49,804 --> 00:14:52,523
- I'll try to keep my feet on the ground.
- I know you will.

102
00:14:52,684 --> 00:14:53,560
Good morning.

103
00:14:54,284 --> 00:14:56,718
For those of you I hired personally...

104
00:14:57,684 --> 00:14:59,720
...it's nice to see you again.

105
00:15:00,484 --> 00:15:04,193
For the rest of you, I am Meredith Vickers.
It's my job to make sure you do yours.

106
00:15:04,684 --> 00:15:07,152
Okay, then. On with the show.

107
00:15:12,524 --> 00:15:14,196
Weyland Corporation.

108
00:15:14,444 --> 00:15:16,355
Building better worlds.

109
00:15:17,604 --> 00:15:19,117
Hello, friends.

110
00:15:21,004 --> 00:15:22,676
My name is Peter Weyland.

111
00:15:24,644 --> 00:15:26,362
I am your employer.

112
00:15:26,604 --> 00:15:31,439
I am recording this, 22 June, 2091.
And if you're watching it...

113
00:15:32,204 --> 00:15:34,274
...you have reached your destination.

114
00:15:34,924 --> 00:15:36,835
And I am long dead.

115
00:15:37,444 --> 00:15:39,321
May I rest in peace.

116
00:15:40,484 --> 00:15:43,521
There's a man sitting with you today.
His name is David.

117
00:15:43,684 --> 00:15:46,596
And he is the closest thing to a son
I will ever have.

118
00:15:46,884 --> 00:15:49,523
Unfortunately, he is not human.

119
00:15:49,804 --> 00:15:50,998
He will never grow old...

120
00:15:51,244 --> 00:15:53,041
...and he will never die.

121
00:15:53,964 --> 00:15:57,001
And yet he is unable to appreciate
these remarkable gifts...

122
00:15:57,164 --> 00:16:01,316
...for that would require the one thing
that David will never have.

123
00:16:01,484 --> 00:16:02,599
A soul.

124
00:16:03,564 --> 00:16:05,236
I have spent my entire...

125
00:16:05,404 --> 00:16:07,759
...lifetime contemplating the questions:

126
00:16:08,044 --> 00:16:09,477
Where do we come from?

127
00:16:09,804 --> 00:16:11,203
What is our purpose?

128
00:16:11,484 --> 00:16:12,837
What happens when we die?

129
00:16:13,524 --> 00:16:17,278
And I have found two people who convinced
me they're on the verge of answering them.

130
00:16:17,964 --> 00:16:20,797
Drs. Holloway and Shaw,
if you would please stand.

131
00:16:23,004 --> 00:16:24,995
As far as you're concerned,
they're in charge.

132
00:16:26,084 --> 00:16:30,475
The Titan Prometheus wanted to give
mankind equal footing with the gods...

133
00:16:30,644 --> 00:16:34,080
...and for that, he was cast from Olympus.

134
00:16:34,924 --> 00:16:39,554
Well, my friends,
the time has finally come for his return.

135
00:16:40,164 --> 00:16:41,074
Doctors, please.

136
00:16:45,244 --> 00:16:46,120
The floor is yours.

137
00:16:54,284 --> 00:16:56,195
Okay, wow.

138
00:16:56,364 --> 00:16:57,683
All right.

139
00:16:57,844 --> 00:16:59,562
I never had to follow a ghost before.

140
00:16:59,924 --> 00:17:01,880
Okay, let me show you why you guys...

141
00:17:02,044 --> 00:17:03,113
...are here.

142
00:17:10,284 --> 00:17:15,233
These are images of archeological digs
from all over the Earth.

143
00:17:15,404 --> 00:17:16,200
That's...

144
00:17:16,364 --> 00:17:19,561
...Egyptian, Mayan, Sumerian, Babylonian.

145
00:17:19,844 --> 00:17:22,517
That's Hawaiian there at the end,
then Mesopotamian.

146
00:17:22,764 --> 00:17:25,642
Now, this one here
is our most recent discovery.

147
00:17:25,804 --> 00:17:29,638
It's a 35,000-year-old cave painting
from the Isle of Skye in Scotland.

148
00:17:29,924 --> 00:17:33,963
These are ancient civilizations.
They were separated by centuries.

149
00:17:34,124 --> 00:17:37,082
They shared no contact with one another,
and yet....

150
00:17:40,764 --> 00:17:41,799
The same pictogram...

151
00:17:41,964 --> 00:17:45,434
...showing men worshipping giant beings,
pointing to the stars...

152
00:17:45,644 --> 00:17:48,477
...was discovered
at every last one of them.

153
00:17:49,004 --> 00:17:51,518
And the only galactic system
that matched...

154
00:17:52,524 --> 00:17:54,958
...was so far from Earth
that there's no way...

155
00:17:55,124 --> 00:17:59,083
...that these primitive, ancient civilizations
could have possibly known about it.

156
00:17:59,244 --> 00:18:00,677
But it just so happens...

157
00:18:02,324 --> 00:18:03,598
...that that system...

158
00:18:05,004 --> 00:18:06,073
...has a sun...

159
00:18:07,084 --> 00:18:08,437
...a lot like ours.

160
00:18:09,444 --> 00:18:13,596
And, based on our long-range scans,
there seemed to be a planet.

161
00:18:14,964 --> 00:18:17,159
Just one planet with a moon...

162
00:18:17,324 --> 00:18:19,121
...capable of sustaining life.

163
00:18:20,524 --> 00:18:22,515
And we arrived there this morning.

164
00:18:24,684 --> 00:18:29,314
So you're saying we're here because of a map
you two kids found in a cave. Is that right?

165
00:18:30,564 --> 00:18:31,792
- No.
- Yeah.

166
00:18:33,964 --> 00:18:36,319
No. Not a map, an invitation.

167
00:18:36,484 --> 00:18:37,803
From who?

168
00:18:39,244 --> 00:18:40,916
We call them Engineers.

169
00:18:41,804 --> 00:18:43,237
Engineers?

170
00:18:43,404 --> 00:18:44,200
Do you mind...

171
00:18:45,204 --> 00:18:46,922
...telling us what they engineered?

172
00:18:48,844 --> 00:18:50,436
They engineered us.

173
00:18:53,084 --> 00:18:53,880
Bullshit.

174
00:18:56,004 --> 00:18:57,801
Okay, so do you...

175
00:18:57,964 --> 00:18:59,556
...have anything to back that up?

176
00:19:00,204 --> 00:19:01,956
Look, if you're willing to discount...

177
00:19:02,124 --> 00:19:03,876
...centuries of Darwinism, that's....

178
00:19:06,964 --> 00:19:07,874
But how do you know?

179
00:19:09,324 --> 00:19:10,598
I don't.

180
00:19:11,084 --> 00:19:13,120
But it's what I choose to believe.

181
00:19:39,884 --> 00:19:40,873
Doctors.

182
00:19:41,924 --> 00:19:45,803
Miss Vickers would like to have
a quick word before the adventure begins.

183
00:19:52,964 --> 00:19:53,919
Wow, nice place.

184
00:19:54,084 --> 00:19:58,043
It's actually a separate module
with its own self-contained life support.

185
00:19:58,484 --> 00:20:00,076
Air, food.

186
00:20:00,364 --> 00:20:03,800
Anything Miss Vickers would need
to survive a hostile environment.

187
00:20:04,044 --> 00:20:05,921
Okay, so she lives on a lifeboat.

188
00:20:06,084 --> 00:20:07,073
Yes.

189
00:20:07,244 --> 00:20:07,881
I do.

190
00:20:08,044 --> 00:20:10,194
I like to minimize risk.

191
00:20:10,764 --> 00:20:14,200
David, why don't you make
the doctors a drink?

192
00:20:14,764 --> 00:20:17,403
I'll take a vodka. Up.

193
00:20:17,804 --> 00:20:19,157
Charlie, look.

194
00:20:19,324 --> 00:20:21,599
It's a Pauling Med-Pod.

195
00:20:21,884 --> 00:20:24,159
They only made a dozen of these.

196
00:20:24,324 --> 00:20:25,120
Miss Shaw.

197
00:20:25,284 --> 00:20:27,639
Please verbally state
the nature of your injury.

198
00:20:28,044 --> 00:20:29,636
Please don't touch that.

199
00:20:29,804 --> 00:20:31,681
It's a very expensive piece of machinery.

200
00:20:32,204 --> 00:20:34,593
It does bypass surgery.
What do you need it for?

201
00:20:36,364 --> 00:20:38,878
There might be some confusion
about our relationship.

202
00:20:39,924 --> 00:20:42,597
Weyland found you impressive enough
to fund this mission.

203
00:20:42,764 --> 00:20:45,153
But I'm fairly certain your Engineers
are scribblings...

204
00:20:45,324 --> 00:20:47,474
...of savages living in dirty little caves.

205
00:20:48,644 --> 00:20:51,556
But let's say I'm wrong,
and you do find these beings down there...

206
00:20:52,684 --> 00:20:54,720
...you won't engage them...

207
00:20:55,004 --> 00:20:56,403
...you won't talk to them.

208
00:20:56,684 --> 00:20:59,198
You will do nothing
but report back to me.

209
00:21:02,604 --> 00:21:04,754
Miss Vickers, is there an agenda that...

210
00:21:04,924 --> 00:21:06,482
...you're not telling us about?

211
00:21:07,044 --> 00:21:07,681
My company...

212
00:21:07,844 --> 00:21:10,278
...paid a trillion dollars to find this place
and bring you.

213
00:21:10,444 --> 00:21:13,117
Had you raised the monies yourself,
Mr. Holloway...

214
00:21:13,284 --> 00:21:16,037
...we'd happily be pursuing your agenda.

215
00:21:17,324 --> 00:21:18,518
But you didn't.

216
00:21:18,924 --> 00:21:20,437
And that makes you an employee.

217
00:21:21,844 --> 00:21:23,755
But if we can't make contact...

218
00:21:23,924 --> 00:21:26,313
...why did you even bring us here?

219
00:21:27,084 --> 00:21:29,723
Weyland was a superstitious man.

220
00:21:30,404 --> 00:21:32,679
He wanted a true believer onboard.

221
00:21:35,244 --> 00:21:36,359
Cheers.

222
00:21:39,564 --> 00:21:40,679
So no response?

223
00:21:41,284 --> 00:21:42,353
I'm sorry, no.

224
00:21:42,524 --> 00:21:44,355
Maybe they didn't understand it.

225
00:21:45,684 --> 00:21:47,640
How are your lessons going, David?

226
00:21:48,804 --> 00:21:52,194
I spent two years deconstructing
dozens of ancient languages...

227
00:21:52,804 --> 00:21:54,362
...to their roots. I'm confident...

228
00:21:54,524 --> 00:21:55,957
...I can communicate with them...

229
00:21:56,204 --> 00:21:58,274
...provided your thesis is correct.

230
00:21:59,524 --> 00:22:01,560
"Provided it's correct." That's good.

231
00:22:01,724 --> 00:22:04,522
That's why they call it a thesis, doctor.

232
00:22:07,484 --> 00:22:09,122
What are you smiling about?

233
00:22:09,284 --> 00:22:11,081
Mr. Ravel, Mr. Chance, take her down.

234
00:22:11,244 --> 00:22:12,677
- Roger that.
- Yes, captain.

235
00:22:13,044 --> 00:22:14,443
Descent trajectory mapped.

236
00:22:14,764 --> 00:22:16,083
How we doing?

237
00:22:16,244 --> 00:22:17,279
Great.

238
00:22:18,444 --> 00:22:19,240
All right, boss.

239
00:22:19,884 --> 00:22:20,634
All personnel...

240
00:22:20,804 --> 00:22:21,919
...this is the captain.

241
00:22:22,084 --> 00:22:23,437
Brace for entry.

242
00:22:23,604 --> 00:22:24,798
Yes, captain.

243
00:22:25,324 --> 00:22:26,757
That means you too, Vickers.

244
00:22:26,924 --> 00:22:27,993
All systems...

245
00:22:28,164 --> 00:22:29,119
...online.

246
00:22:36,164 --> 00:22:37,358
What is the atmosphere?

247
00:22:37,524 --> 00:22:38,673
Atmosphere is...

248
00:22:38,844 --> 00:22:40,038
...71 percent nitrogen...

249
00:22:40,204 --> 00:22:41,319
...21 percent oxygen...

250
00:22:41,484 --> 00:22:42,553
...traces of argon gas.

251
00:22:42,764 --> 00:22:44,755
Whoa, now, that's weather.

252
00:22:44,924 --> 00:22:45,959
Just like home.

253
00:22:46,124 --> 00:22:47,876
If you're breathing
through an exhaust pipe.

254
00:22:48,364 --> 00:22:50,241
CO2 is over 3 percent.

255
00:22:50,404 --> 00:22:52,360
Two minutes without a suit, you're dead.

256
00:22:55,724 --> 00:22:56,793
Peak portside.

257
00:22:57,044 --> 00:22:58,716
Whoa, 52,000!

258
00:22:58,964 --> 00:23:01,000
It makes Everest
look like a baby brother.

259
00:23:01,284 --> 00:23:03,400
All right, take us around.

260
00:23:03,564 --> 00:23:05,236
We'll use that as our point of entry.

261
00:23:07,564 --> 00:23:09,714
Terrain data rezzing up. We've got...

262
00:23:09,884 --> 00:23:11,237
...a couple of hard spots.

263
00:23:11,404 --> 00:23:12,837
Could be metal.

264
00:23:32,804 --> 00:23:33,953
No radio, no heat source.

265
00:23:35,004 --> 00:23:36,039
Nobody's home.

266
00:23:37,244 --> 00:23:38,757
There is nothing in the desert...

267
00:23:39,564 --> 00:23:41,156
...and no man needs nothing.

268
00:23:41,484 --> 00:23:42,678
What was that?

269
00:23:43,884 --> 00:23:45,875
Just something from a film I like.

270
00:23:50,044 --> 00:23:51,397
Let's go through that gateway.

271
00:23:51,684 --> 00:23:53,640
Reduce airspeed by a hundred knots.

272
00:23:58,084 --> 00:24:00,757
Going through. Nice and slow.

273
00:24:06,524 --> 00:24:07,559
Keep it steady, boys.

274
00:24:07,724 --> 00:24:08,361
There.

275
00:24:08,844 --> 00:24:10,436
No, what are you doing?

276
00:24:10,604 --> 00:24:13,357
Dr. Holloway, why don't you take a seat?

277
00:24:14,604 --> 00:24:16,481
Right there. God does not build in...

278
00:24:16,644 --> 00:24:19,636
...straight lines.
Starboard side, this valley! Captain...

279
00:24:19,804 --> 00:24:21,237
...could you put us down there?

280
00:24:21,404 --> 00:24:23,554
I wouldn't be any good
if I couldn't do that.

281
00:24:23,724 --> 00:24:26,921
Mr. Ravel, starboard 90 degrees.

282
00:24:31,604 --> 00:24:34,676
- One mile, port bow.
- One mile, port bow.

283
00:24:34,964 --> 00:24:36,522
Engage landing sequence.

284
00:24:36,684 --> 00:24:37,753
Switch to manual.

285
00:24:37,924 --> 00:24:39,039
- Commence landing.
- Easy.

286
00:24:39,204 --> 00:24:41,160
- Roger that.
- Yeah, baby, yeah.

287
00:24:43,844 --> 00:24:45,163
Bringing her down in five.

288
00:24:45,324 --> 00:24:47,042
- Preparing RCS thrusters.
- Four.

289
00:24:50,564 --> 00:24:52,202
Two. Easy does it.

290
00:25:09,124 --> 00:25:11,718
Generator systems are inactive.

291
00:25:11,884 --> 00:25:14,159
Temperature is at 2.724 K.

292
00:25:25,524 --> 00:25:26,513
Captain, would you...

293
00:25:26,684 --> 00:25:28,595
...tell the survey team to suit up...

294
00:25:28,764 --> 00:25:30,117
...and meet us in the airlock.

295
00:25:30,644 --> 00:25:32,362
Only six hours left of daylight.

296
00:25:32,524 --> 00:25:34,116
- Leave it till morning.
- No, no, no.

297
00:25:34,764 --> 00:25:36,197
It's Christmas, captain...

298
00:25:36,364 --> 00:25:38,161
...and I want to open my presents.

299
00:25:38,444 --> 00:25:39,240
You, boy.

300
00:25:39,404 --> 00:25:40,678
You're coming with us.

301
00:25:41,004 --> 00:25:42,403
I'd be delighted.

302
00:25:47,724 --> 00:25:50,238
Attention: Ramp will open in five minutes.

303
00:25:52,364 --> 00:25:53,877
Hey, Jackson...

304
00:25:54,204 --> 00:25:55,432
...what's that for?

305
00:25:56,164 --> 00:25:57,153
Expedition security.

306
00:25:57,324 --> 00:25:59,792
My job is to make sure
everybody is nice and safe.

307
00:26:01,324 --> 00:26:04,157
This is a scientific expedition.
No weapons.

308
00:26:04,324 --> 00:26:05,313
All right, then.

309
00:26:05,684 --> 00:26:07,003
Good luck with that.

310
00:26:09,804 --> 00:26:11,556
David, why are you wearing a suit, man?

311
00:26:13,004 --> 00:26:14,073
I beg your pardon?

312
00:26:14,244 --> 00:26:15,836
You don't breathe, remember?

313
00:26:16,004 --> 00:26:18,040
So why wear a suit?

314
00:26:18,604 --> 00:26:20,674
I was designed like this...

315
00:26:20,964 --> 00:26:24,877
...because you people are more comfortable
interacting with your own kind.

316
00:26:25,964 --> 00:26:29,161
If I didn't wear the suit,
it would defeat the purpose.

317
00:26:30,084 --> 00:26:31,961
They're making you guys pretty close, huh?

318
00:26:32,524 --> 00:26:33,923
Not too close, I hope.

319
00:26:43,364 --> 00:26:45,798
Attention: Ramp will open in 15 seconds.

320
00:26:50,924 --> 00:26:52,596
Ramp will open in five...

321
00:26:52,764 --> 00:26:56,677
...four, three, two, one.

322
00:27:13,324 --> 00:27:14,598
Hey.

323
00:27:15,244 --> 00:27:17,599
This is just one small step for mankind.

324
00:27:18,444 --> 00:27:19,399
Seriously?

325
00:27:25,324 --> 00:27:27,042
You ready to do this? I know you are.

326
00:27:37,284 --> 00:27:38,194
Hey, Fifield.

327
00:27:38,364 --> 00:27:39,479
I want a spectrograph on this.

328
00:27:39,644 --> 00:27:41,794
I want to know if it's natural
or if somebody put it there.

329
00:27:41,964 --> 00:27:44,524
I can't tell you if it's natural or not.
But what I can...

330
00:27:44,684 --> 00:27:46,720
...tell you is, it's hollow.

331
00:28:09,884 --> 00:28:13,479
Prometheus, are you seeing this?

332
00:28:13,804 --> 00:28:14,919
Affirmative.

333
00:28:15,244 --> 00:28:16,472
We see it.

334
00:28:23,404 --> 00:28:24,041
Okay, ready?

335
00:28:24,204 --> 00:28:25,603
- Yeah.
- Let's do it.

336
00:28:57,684 --> 00:28:59,720
- After you.
- After you.

337
00:28:59,884 --> 00:29:00,794
Okay.

338
00:29:00,964 --> 00:29:01,953
Careful.

339
00:29:02,604 --> 00:29:04,515
Prometheus, we're going in.

340
00:29:04,684 --> 00:29:05,799
Copy that.

341
00:29:37,964 --> 00:29:38,760
What's back here?

342
00:29:38,924 --> 00:29:40,960
Some kind of a corridor?

343
00:29:41,804 --> 00:29:44,318
Mr. Fifield,
let's get a grid of the structure.

344
00:29:44,484 --> 00:29:45,803
I want the whole interior.

345
00:29:46,764 --> 00:29:48,959
If there's anything in here
worth looking at...

346
00:29:49,124 --> 00:29:50,352
...these pups'll find them.

347
00:29:50,964 --> 00:29:51,874
"Pups"?

348
00:29:52,044 --> 00:29:54,274
Yeah, pups. My pups.

349
00:30:08,484 --> 00:30:11,123
Prometheus, we are now mapping.

350
00:30:15,244 --> 00:30:16,279
Copy that.

351
00:30:28,124 --> 00:30:29,079
Well, I'll be damned.

352
00:30:43,204 --> 00:30:44,398
Fifield, you got a read?

353
00:30:44,564 --> 00:30:45,633
Yeah.

354
00:30:46,364 --> 00:30:49,162
Pups are saying this way.

355
00:31:07,004 --> 00:31:08,357
Look at this.

356
00:31:15,404 --> 00:31:16,962
Oh, Charlie.

357
00:31:20,804 --> 00:31:21,793
Jesus.

358
00:31:22,124 --> 00:31:23,876
The sunlight is heating the water.

359
00:31:24,524 --> 00:31:26,037
Check out the humidity.

360
00:31:26,204 --> 00:31:27,762
Yeah, and look at the CO2 levels.

361
00:31:28,244 --> 00:31:29,279
Outside...

362
00:31:29,444 --> 00:31:31,400
...it's completely toxic, and in here...

363
00:31:31,564 --> 00:31:33,555
...there's nothing. It's breathable.

364
00:31:35,564 --> 00:31:37,077
What are you doing?

365
00:31:37,244 --> 00:31:39,394
- Don't be an idiot.
- Don't be a skeptic.

366
00:31:39,884 --> 00:31:41,920
There's something
generating an atmosphere.

367
00:31:42,284 --> 00:31:43,478
David?

368
00:31:43,644 --> 00:31:45,714
- Dr. Holloway is correct.
- Cleaner than Earth...

369
00:31:45,884 --> 00:31:46,999
...actually.

370
00:31:47,164 --> 00:31:48,040
They were terraforming.

371
00:31:48,364 --> 00:31:49,763
Please don't do--

372
00:31:49,924 --> 00:31:51,642
I'm not wearing this thing anymore.

373
00:31:52,164 --> 00:31:53,392
Wish me luck, baby.

374
00:31:53,564 --> 00:31:56,032
Do you copy?
Do not remove your headgear.

375
00:32:11,964 --> 00:32:13,795
You crazy bastard.

376
00:32:18,284 --> 00:32:19,478
Connect our suit cameras...

377
00:32:19,644 --> 00:32:23,717
...if you want to continue watching this
freak show. We are taking our helmets off.

378
00:32:24,804 --> 00:32:26,442
Copy that. Switching feeds.

379
00:32:28,364 --> 00:32:30,434
Well, come on. Pay up.

380
00:32:31,124 --> 00:32:33,718
- Pay what?
- What do you mean, "Pay what"?

381
00:32:33,884 --> 00:32:37,240
Something is manufacturing
breathable air down there. That, mate...

382
00:32:37,404 --> 00:32:40,043
- ...is terraforming.
- No, no. The bet was why we came here.

383
00:32:40,204 --> 00:32:42,957
If you said a dead old man wanted
to talk to Martians, I'd pay.

384
00:32:43,124 --> 00:32:44,443
Come on, a hundred credits.

385
00:32:44,604 --> 00:32:47,484
Put it towards a lap dance with
Miss Vickers. How about that?

386
00:32:49,484 --> 00:32:51,554
It's minus 12 in here.

387
00:32:51,724 --> 00:32:53,760
So why is this water not frozen?

388
00:32:53,924 --> 00:32:55,277
Maybe it ain't water.

389
00:32:56,004 --> 00:32:57,403
Maybe it's Martian piss.

390
00:32:59,364 --> 00:33:02,276
That's your scientific theory?

391
00:33:02,444 --> 00:33:04,275
Is it? Mr. Biology?

392
00:33:08,324 --> 00:33:10,121
Whatever it is, it sure is collagenous.

393
00:33:11,204 --> 00:33:12,842
Some kind of sediment, perhaps.

394
00:33:32,044 --> 00:33:33,159
Impressive.

395
00:33:52,044 --> 00:33:52,760
What was that?

396
00:33:53,644 --> 00:33:54,793
David?

397
00:33:55,644 --> 00:33:56,281
David?

398
00:33:57,644 --> 00:33:58,838
What is that?

399
00:34:00,764 --> 00:34:01,640
David?

400
00:34:09,964 --> 00:34:11,238
Ellie!

401
00:34:15,884 --> 00:34:16,680
What was that?

402
00:34:17,444 --> 00:34:19,241
I'm really glad we didn't bring weapons.

403
00:34:19,404 --> 00:34:21,599
- Come on, El. Let's go.
- Whose idea was that?

404
00:34:22,004 --> 00:34:22,914
Keep up!

405
00:34:25,244 --> 00:34:25,881
Come on!

406
00:34:33,524 --> 00:34:34,798
Where did he go?

407
00:34:39,884 --> 00:34:41,397
Wait, wait, wait.

408
00:34:46,164 --> 00:34:49,122
There it is. There it is. There it is.

409
00:34:50,084 --> 00:34:52,473
Oh, my God, Charlie. We found them.

410
00:34:52,644 --> 00:34:54,123
What do you mean "them"?

411
00:34:55,364 --> 00:34:56,717
It is them, Ellie.

412
00:34:57,484 --> 00:34:58,997
It looks like a door...

413
00:34:59,364 --> 00:35:03,152
...and he's been decapitated by it.

414
00:35:04,364 --> 00:35:05,797
Son of a bitch.

415
00:35:07,484 --> 00:35:08,803
They were right.

416
00:35:12,164 --> 00:35:14,155
What did you want them to be? Wrong?

417
00:35:17,804 --> 00:35:18,873
David...

418
00:35:19,564 --> 00:35:21,156
...please tell me you can read that.

419
00:35:21,804 --> 00:35:22,998
Perhaps.

420
00:35:25,164 --> 00:35:26,756
No, I'm out of here.

421
00:35:28,684 --> 00:35:30,436
Hey, Fifield, where are you going?

422
00:35:32,044 --> 00:35:33,079
What?

423
00:35:34,764 --> 00:35:37,324
Look, I'm just a geologist.

424
00:35:37,484 --> 00:35:39,554
I like rocks. I love rocks!

425
00:35:40,004 --> 00:35:42,359
Now it's clear
you two don't give a shit about rocks.

426
00:35:42,524 --> 00:35:44,992
But what you do seem to care about
is gigantic dead...

427
00:35:45,164 --> 00:35:45,835
...bodies.

428
00:35:46,004 --> 00:35:48,916
As I don't really have anything
to contribute in the gigantic...

429
00:35:49,084 --> 00:35:50,437
...dead body arena...

430
00:35:51,884 --> 00:35:55,274
...I want to go back to the ship,
if you don't mind.

431
00:35:58,604 --> 00:35:59,320
Anyone wanna...

432
00:35:59,484 --> 00:36:01,520
...join me, hey? You staying?

433
00:36:03,164 --> 00:36:04,153
No, ship's good.

434
00:36:04,324 --> 00:36:06,440
Yeah. Ship very good.

435
00:36:07,364 --> 00:36:10,276
Congratulations on meeting your maker.

436
00:36:11,044 --> 00:36:12,193
Thank you.

437
00:36:12,844 --> 00:36:13,560
Pull yourself...

438
00:36:13,724 --> 00:36:14,600
...together, man.

439
00:36:17,924 --> 00:36:20,764
And I thought you were the crazy one.

440
00:36:28,324 --> 00:36:30,042
Do you have the carbon reader?

441
00:36:32,364 --> 00:36:33,592
Thank you.

442
00:36:39,564 --> 00:36:40,679
How long's it been dead?

443
00:36:43,324 --> 00:36:44,359
Two thousand years...

444
00:36:44,524 --> 00:36:45,639
...give or take.

445
00:36:49,084 --> 00:36:50,597
What are you doing, David?

446
00:36:51,524 --> 00:36:53,162
I'm attempting to open the door.

447
00:36:53,324 --> 00:36:55,519
Wait. We don't know
what's on the other side.

448
00:36:57,804 --> 00:36:59,157
Oops. Sorry.

449
00:37:03,644 --> 00:37:05,874
Look, Ford. It's the head.

450
00:37:15,924 --> 00:37:18,119
An amazing state of preservation.

451
00:37:18,404 --> 00:37:20,076
- We'll take it in.
- Yeah.

452
00:37:24,004 --> 00:37:25,483
Remarkably human.

453
00:37:42,444 --> 00:37:44,036
Beautiful painting.

454
00:37:45,124 --> 00:37:46,352
It's a mural.

455
00:37:58,444 --> 00:37:59,081
Stop.

456
00:37:59,244 --> 00:38:00,359
Stop. Don't touch it.

457
00:38:00,524 --> 00:38:01,593
Sorry.

458
00:38:02,684 --> 00:38:04,595
Please, don't touch anything.

459
00:38:05,484 --> 00:38:06,121
Sweating.

460
00:38:43,484 --> 00:38:44,633
Organic.

461
00:38:50,924 --> 00:38:51,879
Oh, no.

462
00:38:52,164 --> 00:38:54,758
Charlie, the murals are changing.

463
00:38:54,924 --> 00:38:57,233
I think we've affected the atmosphere
in the room.

464
00:38:57,404 --> 00:38:59,235
Charlie, do you copy?

465
00:39:00,204 --> 00:39:01,000
Oh, the head!

466
00:39:01,284 --> 00:39:03,275
Ford, quick, help me bag the head!

467
00:39:14,444 --> 00:39:15,877
- Boss.
- What you got?

468
00:39:16,844 --> 00:39:18,675
We got an incoming storm front.

469
00:39:18,844 --> 00:39:19,959
Silica...

470
00:39:20,124 --> 00:39:22,035
...and lots of static. This is not good.

471
00:39:22,204 --> 00:39:22,920
I see it.

472
00:39:26,844 --> 00:39:27,674
Ground crew...

473
00:39:27,844 --> 00:39:28,799
...this is Janek.

474
00:39:28,964 --> 00:39:30,716
I need you to hustle back right now.

475
00:39:31,004 --> 00:39:32,437
Ground crew, do you copy me?

476
00:39:32,604 --> 00:39:33,878
I got 200-kilometer...

477
00:39:34,044 --> 00:39:35,523
...winds of airborne silica...

478
00:39:35,684 --> 00:39:37,117
...and enough static to fry your suit.

479
00:39:37,284 --> 00:39:38,717
Copy that, sir.

480
00:39:38,884 --> 00:39:39,794
We need more time.

481
00:39:40,484 --> 00:39:41,758
I'll be closing the outer...

482
00:39:41,924 --> 00:39:43,073
...doors in 15 minutes.

483
00:39:43,244 --> 00:39:45,314
I sincerely hope you can make it.

484
00:39:47,964 --> 00:39:49,795
Charlie! David!

485
00:39:50,364 --> 00:39:51,399
We must leave now.

486
00:39:53,484 --> 00:39:55,076
This is just another tomb.

487
00:39:59,404 --> 00:40:00,553
David!

488
00:40:03,324 --> 00:40:05,121
- On three.
- Two, three, up.

489
00:40:05,284 --> 00:40:06,603
Let's go!

490
00:40:07,324 --> 00:40:08,996
Easy, easy, easy. Careful.

491
00:40:11,964 --> 00:40:14,558
David, we are leaving!

492
00:40:23,724 --> 00:40:24,520
Come on!

493
00:40:24,684 --> 00:40:26,322
Damn it, they've already taken off.

494
00:40:26,484 --> 00:40:27,394
Come on, let's go.

495
00:40:29,004 --> 00:40:31,996
Prometheus to ground crew.
You're running out of time.

496
00:40:32,164 --> 00:40:34,120
All right, come on. Let's go.

497
00:40:48,764 --> 00:40:50,117
Go faster!

498
00:41:13,004 --> 00:41:14,119
Charlie! The head!

499
00:41:15,044 --> 00:41:15,556
Ellie, no!

500
00:41:15,724 --> 00:41:16,361
What are you doing?

501
00:41:24,804 --> 00:41:25,554
Hatch closure...

502
00:41:25,724 --> 00:41:26,713
- ...in five seconds.
- Shit.

503
00:41:27,924 --> 00:41:28,674
Damn it, hold on!

504
00:41:30,924 --> 00:41:31,674
Goddamn it.

505
00:41:31,844 --> 00:41:32,913
Door closing.

506
00:41:35,044 --> 00:41:36,079
Ellie, don't move!

507
00:41:41,084 --> 00:41:41,721
Charlie!

508
00:41:45,124 --> 00:41:46,113
Grab my hand!

509
00:41:56,844 --> 00:41:57,242
No!

510
00:41:58,324 --> 00:41:59,200
No, Ellie!

511
00:41:59,364 --> 00:42:00,114
Ellie!

512
00:42:36,844 --> 00:42:37,799
Got it.

513
00:42:45,444 --> 00:42:47,196
So, what was that, Ellie?

514
00:42:47,484 --> 00:42:49,793
You could've compromised the mission.
Not to mention...

515
00:42:49,964 --> 00:42:51,363
...almost killing yourself!

516
00:42:51,524 --> 00:42:52,479
Are you all right?

517
00:42:52,844 --> 00:42:54,163
Yes.

518
00:42:54,444 --> 00:42:55,559
Thank you, David.

519
00:42:56,044 --> 00:42:57,477
My pleasure.

520
00:42:57,804 --> 00:42:59,556
Doctors, it's real good to have...

521
00:42:59,724 --> 00:43:01,919
...you back,
but where's Millburn and Fifield?

522
00:43:02,084 --> 00:43:03,722
Aren't they back yet?

523
00:43:05,164 --> 00:43:06,597
- Get them up for me.
- All right.

524
00:43:09,404 --> 00:43:11,076
We've been here before, Fifield.

525
00:43:11,244 --> 00:43:13,804
I don't know. It all looks the same to me.

526
00:43:14,724 --> 00:43:16,680
Boys, this is the captain. Listen up.

527
00:43:17,244 --> 00:43:19,883
Between the static electricity
and the wind speed...

528
00:43:20,044 --> 00:43:22,239
...well, there ain't no safe way
to come get you.

529
00:43:22,844 --> 00:43:23,560
What?

530
00:43:23,724 --> 00:43:27,080
The temperature is dropping rapidly,
so get your helmets on and stay warm...

531
00:43:27,724 --> 00:43:29,635
...until the storm passes.

532
00:43:29,804 --> 00:43:30,600
Captain...

533
00:43:30,884 --> 00:43:33,956
...can you get a message to the scientist
and his zealot girlfriend?

534
00:43:35,084 --> 00:43:36,073
You got a pen nearby?

535
00:43:36,244 --> 00:43:38,075
No. No, I think we got it.

536
00:43:38,684 --> 00:43:40,515
Tell them I said... themselves.

537
00:43:41,644 --> 00:43:42,440
Copy?

538
00:43:42,604 --> 00:43:44,754
Copy that.
All right, boys, keep your head down...

539
00:43:44,924 --> 00:43:47,119
...and we'll come get you in the morning.

540
00:43:48,804 --> 00:43:49,759
Well, which way now?

541
00:43:49,924 --> 00:43:50,674
All right.

542
00:43:50,844 --> 00:43:52,800
Well, which way, huh?

543
00:44:06,204 --> 00:44:08,115
Sample is sterile. No contagion present.

544
